profile_1996_qwen3:30b.think_process: Politics? I don't even know what to say about that. I'm 20, got no job, and I'm just trying to get by with my family. The politicians are all rich people who don't care about us. They talk about elections and stuff but never help people like me who can't even find work. I've seen it on TV—just more promises that go nowhere. Why should I waste my time being interested in something that doesn't change anything for me? I'm too busy trying to find a job or help my mom pay for food.

profile_1997_qwen3:30b.think_process: Mierda, otra encuesta sobre política. ¿Qué va a entender un político de lo que me pasa a mí todos los días? Yo voy a trabajar de ventas en el centro, atiendo clientes que se quejan porque el pan subió 20 pesos y después mi jefe me dice que si no vendo más, me despiden. Mi carrera universitaria no me sirvió para nada aquí, pero no me hago ilusiones: los políticos hablan de "futuro" y yo necesito el dinero para el alquiler y la leche de mi nena. Vimos cómo se robaron todo con el último gobierno y ahora otro promete cosas pero nada cambia. No, no me interesa, no quiero perder el tiempo escuchando promesas que nunca cumplen. Ya me da igual.

profile_1998_qwen3:30b.think_process: I see my dad talking about politics on TV sometimes, but it's always about those poor neighborhoods and people fighting over money that they don't even have. My family's got a nice house in Puerto Madero and we don't need to worry about that stuff. I'm not like some kid from the barrio who has to care about who gets elected to do something for them. I just go to my classes, hang out with my friends at the mall, and get whatever I want. Politics feels like a thing for people who don't have anything to lose. What's the point of getting interested when it's not gonna change anything for me? I don't even know who the candidates are half the time.

profile_1999_qwen3:30b.think_process: As a 42-year-old sales manager in Buenos Aires with a university degree, politics is part of life but not my priority. I follow economic policies because they affect my commission and client relationships—like how inflation impacts pricing strategies—but I don’t spend time on partisan debates. My family and business require my focus; I get news from brief articles or radio during my commute, not deep dives. Politics feels distant when my daily work is about securing deals and managing a team, not ideological fights. I’m aware of the major parties, but I’m not motivated to engage beyond voting—most discussions feel recycled or irrelevant to my actual job. So, not very interested, just pragmatic.

profile_2000_qwen3:30b.think_process: Mira, yo soy un vendedor de productos básicos en Buenos Aires, me levanto a las 6 para llegar al trabajo antes que los demás. Tengo que pagar el alquiler y la luz cada mes, y los políticos siempre hablan de cosas que no me llegan a mí. El último gobierno prometió mejorar el salario pero nada cambió, solo subieron los precios del pan y la leche. ¿Para qué me voy a meter en política si todo es mentira? Yo me monto en el colectivo, hago mis ventas, y después me voy a mi casa a ver a mi familia. Mejor que me enfoque en lo que sí veo todos los días, no en eso de los partidos y las promesas vacías. No me interesa nada de eso, ya sé que nada va a cambiar para mí.

profile_2002_qwen3:30b.think_process: Hombre, politics? I been working sales all my life, trying to put food on the table for my kids. Every time they change the government, it's all talk about "new plans" but then the price of gas goes up and my pension barely covers the medicine I need. I heard about Perón back in the day, but now it's just politicians arguing on TV while we're stuck paying more for everything. My job is to sell shoes and fix the cash register, not to worry about who's gonna be president next week. My son says it's important to vote, but what good does that do? I've seen too many elections come and go, and nothing changes for us in the barrio. I just want to get by and not worry about all the noise. Why should I care?

profile_2006_qwen3:30b.think_process: Mierda, otra encuesta política. Yo soy un hombre de 48 años que trabaja en la fábrica de acero desde los 25, aunque saqué una licenciatura en Administración que nunca sirvió para nada. ¿Interesado en política? Mira, en la tele siempre hablan de cosas que no nos llegan: impuestos, elecciones, gastos públicos... pero cuando yo necesito pagar el pasaje del colectivo para llegar a trabajar, ¿qué me importa si el presidente es de derecha o izquierda? Mis hijos están en el colegio privado porque no hay otra opción, y cada mes la inflación me roba un 10% más de lo que gano. Los políticos prometen, prometen, y al final siempre es lo mismo: suben el gas, bajan los sueldos, y nosotros seguimos pagando. Me parece que si me meto en política, solo me darán más problemas sin resolver ninguno. Hoy me duele la espalda por el trabajo y mi esposa está enferma, ¿para qué voy a perder tiempo pensando en lo que pasa en el Congreso?

profile_2007_qwen3:30b.think_process: I'm 38, work as a technician at a small Buenos Aires factory, got my degree but it didn't lift me out of the lower middle class. My wife works in admin, we're barely making rent with inflation eating everything. I see the politicians on TV promising things but nothing changes for us – the prices keep rising, the roads are bad, and the same old parties keep swapping seats. I tried to pay attention when I was younger, but it just made me angry seeing how they don't listen to people like me. Now I'm just focused on getting my job done, paying the bills, and keeping my kids fed. What would caring about politics even do for me right now? It's all smoke and mirrors. I'm too tired to waste energy on something that won't fix my bus fare or the grocery bill.
